reviews_data.review_text: Delicious coffee and super friendly staff.

I get a cappuccino every time I come in, and it never disappoints! The quality is always consistent, and the espresso has such rich, smooth notes. It’s genuinely delicious every single time. Easily one of my favorite spots for coffee.
Nice place for a drink

The atmosphere of the place seems great. Lots of places to sit and outdoor seating. However the cold brew doesn't taste like cold brew, but coffee that was brewed hot and then left to be cooled down. It's just not very good and a bit weak as an iced coffee.

I also had a weird interaction with an employee who asked me to hand the menu back to him, without explanation, and then placed it back down on the counter where I picked it up from. I could understand if this was the only menu, but he then placed another one on top.

So I guess you can't look at the menu before you start your order? Which seemed a bit odd.

Anyway, not horrible but I don't have any reason to come back.

reviews_data.owner_answer: Thanks for coming in - sorry you did not enjoy it- our cold brew is made cold as traditional cold brew. Just to clarify- so sorry it wasn’t your taste.

reviews_data.review_text: Amazing seasonal coffee!

I love this spot. Welcoming, trendy(but not contrived), nice selection of wines and treats. Great place to WFH during the week, with ample space to sit and lovely spot for off-duty hangs as well. The coffee is great and staff are super friendly.

What a great coffee house, wine, beer and cocktails. Such a lovely aesthetic and cozy comfy and neighborhood (Noda)atmosphere. We loved it and the huge ‘Cinnamon Roll’ plus a perfect ‘Flat White’ ♥️☕️♥️ what a great start to this day !!
Vanilla Flat White and Cheddar Biscuit are a must - 5 stars all around!! Tons of indoor and outdoor seating and staff are great as well!
Consistently best espresso in Charlotte (at least on par w/ Hex). Can get a little busy.

reviews_data.review_text:
I always judge a coffee shop off its iced oat milk lattes, and unfortunately this one was a bit on the weak side. The espresso itself seemed to have a good flavor, but I felt like it was just one shot short of being well-balanced with the oat milk. I’d love to come back and try it hot or with an extra shot to see if that improves it!

Aside from that, I had a fig & orange muffin (crazy delicious), and the bottle shop and atmosphere was fantastic! It had lots of folks hanging out even on a monday evening, and their wine and beer selection was very impressive. There was a great mix of folks working on their laptops and just hanging out, so the environment is definitely a blend of work and chill. Shoutout to the super friendly barista as well! The whole cafe really was lovely, so I do wish the coffee had followed suit. Maybe next time!

reviews_data.review_text:
First, I'm really glad I visited. I had a good experience. I had wanted somewhere I could get something to eat, something to drink and spend some time writing. So I googled places and found this one. I read a review where someone said he'd "never seen more outlets," and it also popped up on my search for "good places to dine solo in Charlotte." It was pretty packed, I must say, from the patio facing the street, to the bar, to the front and middle of the place but I finally found a table in the back where the group I saw when I came in had vacated. That's where my picture is from. I kind of wish I had taken some up front because it was a very cool vibe. I got an everything bagel with cream cheese and a mimosa, and then later a proseco. Since I had researched before I went I asked about a food menu becaue I thought I had read there was more food than what I saw. I'm still not sure where that came from but when you click on this review it gives you the option for recommended dishes such as eggs benedict with home fries (as of 4/21/2025), so maybe that's where I got the idea and maybe that should be removed? But it's just pastries and bagels and that was fine once I was there.

Also, I did not realize there was a parking lot until I drove up the street with many cars parked parallel on the side and went in a horseshoe around a neighborhood. Luckily, there was a parking space available but I could tell if someone came at a busy time, it might be difficult. I would go back and probably will.

review_questions.Parking options: Free parking lot

reviews_data.review_text: The place is cool. They have good coffee & I love the spinach feta croissant. My only complaint is that the tall guy that works there is always rude to me no matter how polite I am. It really discourages me from wanting to patronize the place.

A Cozy Gem That’s Perfect for Work & Catch-Ups**

I’m definitely in my coffee shop phase, so finding The Hobbyist was a total win. I stopped by to meet up with a colleague and chat through some work, and the **atmosphere was so inviting** that we ended up staying well past our planned hour.

We both ordered lattes, which were smooth and well-crafted. There’s plenty of seating, but I can see how it might get crowded during peak hours—so don’t be surprised if you end up sharing a table. The **staff was friendly**, and the overall vibe really sparked creativity and focus.

The Hobbyist has officially been added to my coffee shop rotation. Whether you’re working, meeting a friend, or just want a quality cup in a cozy setting, this spot delivers.

reviews_data.review_text: This place is great but the service was very bad. It is mostly filled with  an under 35 crowd and my partner and I are considerably older. We sat down at the bar and waited for 20 min. For anyone to even acknowledge that we were there. It is a shame because we really like the ambiance and the drinks were great AND we are amazing tippers when we get decent service. Hopefully the owners will work on improving the seemingly discriminatory service. (3 people came in way after us and the servers were on it & they get their order before we even had a hello.

reviews_data.owner_answer: Sorry for any miscommunications- however, we do have silverware available and since our pastries are brought in from local bakers and not made in house, we do offer to heat those up in the oven- so that would fix that issue. reviews_data.review_text:
I live in the neighborhood and want to like this place but the service is just as bad today as it was the first week they opened. I’ve been here too many times where I either have to wait an eternity for the bar staff to acknowledge me or I need to flag down the employee right in front of me to get a second round or cash out. Their staff always appears to be completely oblivious to anyone sitting at the bar.

Two or three people working a bar should never have an issue handling 12-14 bar seats and a walk up counter. And one shouldn’t have sit for 10-15 minutes being overlooked without a menu or a drink while the bartenders decide it’s time to do some spot cleaning while chatting with one another.

reviews_data.review_text:
This cafe and bar's spacious layout with all the wood and plants really caught my eye - honestly, it left more of an impression than the drinks.

The menu looked so good that I was tempted to go for a cocktail, but we had a packed day ahead. Since my friend and I are lightweights, we stuck with a matcha latte and a chai latte instead.

The matcha was subtle but had a bit more flavor than most places. They've got all sorts of seating options - big tables, small ones - so it seems like a chill spot to hang out when it's not busy.

Kinda bummed we couldn't try the cocktails, but it was still a nice break. Might have to come back when we've got more time to kill!

The owners spent an especially large effort making sure to stock bottles of wine and cans of beer you wouldn't see elsewhere. That hasn't changed so much but the vibe certainly has. reviews_data.review_text: Great spot to post up got coffee during the day or a drink at night and work, socialise, or catch live music in Friday nights. They have good coffee and a great wine and beer by the bottle selection

I stopped in here this morning and ordered a creme brulee latte with a raspberry cream cheese danish. Before we get into the coffee and danish, let me say that I was really digging the design and vibe of this place. They managed to accomplish a more classy and intimate setting, but at the same time it was also laid back and easy going. I found this to be a unique combination of atmospheres for a coffee shop. Although, they do have wine and a good whiskey selection so that may be why there is an overlap in the settings that I was experiencing. I also appreciated the no laptops on the weekends concept that they have implemented. Even though I didn't find myself chatting with any locals, which is what they stated the goal of this concept is, I think it's a great idea! I find that we too often bury ourselves into technology and forget to experience the things around us. It's a step in the right direction, and a good way to increase the interactions among others. Now, back to the coffee and danish. The creme brulee latte was spot on and the danish was exactly what I needed to get my morning started. I liked the location of this place, and I definitely see The Hobbyist being one of my go to coffee shops!
reviews_data.owner_answer: Thank you for coming in and we are so happy you appreciate our style and atmosphere. We also enjoy a little time turned off from technology so thanks for supporting us! Come back and see us!

reviews_data.review_text: Ordered a hot latte. Right amount of foam and great tasting overall. Staff was super friendly. 5/5

Espresso is fruity👍. Cold brew is strong (guess it is from a dark roast blend)  wait time is long (I know it takes time to make a good coffee, but if you prefer to get in and out quickly, just be aware).
Probably my favorite coffee shop

Been a few times while house sitting for a friend. It’s always over a ten minute wait to get my latte, even when no drinks in line in front of me. Barista’s seem to busy chatting or flirting with people, than to make the orders! Todays latte not only took 10 minutes, but the milk was burnt!

reviews_data.review_text: Overall nice spot. Visited from Chicago yesterday and my only complaint is that the barista didn’t know what a cortado was. I ordered a cortado and got a short latte—way too much milk. Please educate the staff on how to make a proper cortado. It’s not a short latte!
reviews_data.owner_answer: Hi Janelle- thanks for visiting us from Chicago! We are so sorry you did not like the proportions of our cortado- we do a 1:1 ratio double shot of espresso and steamed milk. We are always happy to help you get exactly what you are looking for- maybe a macchiato, or just a less than 1:1 ratio. Again, so sorry it wasn’t exactly what you were looking for!

reviews_data.review_text: My new favorite coffee shop in Charlotte! Great coffee with a twist 😉 And the Old Fashioned was good too. Best of all, the vibe and the live music!
reviews_data.owner_answer: So glad you enjoyed it! Thanks so much!

reviews_data.review_text: Cute little coffee shop that has lounge areas and an outside patio with a very relaxed atmosphere. Drinks were good, awesome place for meeting with friends, working, a date, or just to relax with coffee and a book!
Beautiful and delicious cappuccino.  Also had a croissant which was buttery and flaky.  Service impeccable.
Cutest little place with great coffee!
The coffee is good, nothing crazy but very solid. Interior is really nice, great place to work.

I want so badly to like this place. But I just can’t. Walking distance from our house and we have come here a ton of times but literally every time we come there is a hilariously bad interaction. Whether it’s the cashier telling us there was “no way to know” whether a pastry was vegetarian or not, being scolded for having our dog on a leash while we ordered only to see the same manager petting a dog in line the next time we were there or waiting 10 minutes for a cold pastry to be placed in a bag it’s always some completely avoidable example of poor service. My breaking point to leave this review was being charged 45 cents for water (which I had to fill myself) after we paid $19 for two coffees and one pastry. I get it. Cups cost money. And our service was very friendly (and apologetic) this time. I’ve never left a Google review before but please make some changes, The Hobbyist.
reviews_data.owner_answer: Thanks for visiting us and we apologize if you’ve had a frustrating experience. Our staff work hard to try and deliver good customer service. We source from multiple local bakers and one of them is always vegan (on Saturdays and Sundays) and one has some vegan options during the week, it may be that you are asking about a pastry that is not from them so is likely not vegan- the staff may be telling you they don’t know for sure because it’s not stated from the baker. So I would stick with the items that are labeled vegan from the baker. Unfortunately pets that are not service animals are not allowed in, due to health code, as always things slip by and sometimes people order with their dogs- and we LOVE dogs but have to be careful with health code around food. I am sorry about that as well. We do have to have some global rules for water cups as these are the same cups we serve beverages in and being on a main street people come in all the time and just ask for water- so we cover our cup expenses for that being just a single small business. Our water source for filling is filtered and self servicing like many shops, so you can fill your own container and cut down on cup waste and cost that way as well. Again, our mission is of course to provide great neighborhood service and we always are striving to improve with every staff member every day. So we will discuss ways to improve our service based off of your review as well.

Before we get into the coffee and danish, let me say that I was really digging the design and vibe of this place. They managed to accomplish a more classy and intimate setting, but at the same time it was also laid back and easy going. I found this to be a unique combination of atmospheres for a coffee shop. Although, they do have wine and a good whiskey selection so that may be why there is an overlap in the settings that I was experiencing. I also appreciated the no laptops on the weekends concept that they have implemented. Even though I didn't find myself chatting with any locals, which is what they stated the goal of this concept is, I think it's a great idea! I find that we too often bury ourselves into technology and forget to experience the things around us. It's a step in the right direction, and a good way to increase the interactions among others. Now, back to the coffee and danish. The creme brulee latte was spot on and the danish was exactly what I needed to get my morning started. I liked the location of this place, and I definitely see The Hobbyist being one of my go to coffee shops!

reviews_data.review_text: Cute little coffee shop that has lounge areas and an outside patio with a very relaxed atmosphere. Drinks were good, awesome place for meeting with friends, working, a date, or just to relax with coffee and a book!

I want so badly to like this place. But I just can’t. Walking distance from our house and we have come here a ton of times but literally every time we come there is a hilariously bad interaction. Whether it’s the cashier telling us there was “no way to know” whether a pastry was vegetarian or not, being scolded for having our dog on a leash while we ordered only to see the same manager petting a dog in line the next time we were there or waiting 10 minutes for a cold pastry to be placed in a bag it’s always some completely avoidable example of poor service. My breaking point to leave this review was being charged 45 cents for water (which I had to fill myself) after we paid $19 for two coffees and one pastry. I get it. Cups cost money. And our service was very friendly (and apologetic) this time. I’ve never left a Google review before but please make some changes, The Hobbyist.
reviews_data.owner_answer: Thanks for visiting us and we apologize if you’ve had a frustrating experience. Our staff work hard to try and deliver good customer service. We source from multiple local bakers and one of them is always vegan (on Saturdays and Sundays) and one has some vegan options during the week, it may be that you are asking about a pastry that is not from them so is likely not vegan- the staff may be telling you they don’t know for sure because it’s not stated from the baker. So I would stick with the items that are labeled vegan from the baker. Unfortunately pets that are not service animals are not allowed in, due to health code, as always things slip by and sometimes people order with their dogs- and we LOVE dogs but have to be careful with health code around food. I am sorry about that as well. We do have to have some global rules for water cups as these are the same cups we serve beverages in and being on a main street people come in all the time and just ask for water- so we cover our cup expenses for that being just a single small business. Our water source for filling is filtered and self servicing like many shops, so you can fill your own container and cut down on cup waste and cost that way as well. Again, our mission is of course to provide great neighborhood service and we always are striving to improve with every staff member every day. So we will discuss ways to improve our service based off of your review as well.

reviews_data.review_text: This is a forewarning for anyone looking to study or work on the weekends. This is also not a review of the staff, the beverages, or the ambiance, but I felt like this was an important message. I went to prepare for the work week on Sunday afternoon and found the tables riddled with small "No Laptop" signs on the tables. At the time, my initial thinking was that the establishment did not want computers on the furniture (because the alternative, banning them completely, seemed absured given that I regularly worked at The Hobbyist this summer. Shortly after getting my tea did one of the employees let me know about their new "unplug policy" on the weekends to give patrons a chance to connect with one another in person (although, when I looked around, the policy didn't seem to be efficacious). On the weekends, I sometimes need to get out of the house and complete work in a neutral space with other people who are similar in that regard, but I feel that this recent policy overplays its hand and falls short of the intended goals. Restricting patron's autonomy and choice in the entire space detracts from the neutrality of what I feel a coffee shop represents.
